profile_positions.description:
DuCHA is part of TNO and delivers innovative solutions for creating optimum healthcare settings 

•	Developed  strategy for business growth and integration within TNO;
•	Established and forged strong alliances with strategic partners;
•	Effectively managed, led and executed multiple research projects in the field of healthcare;
•	Developed OAZIS+, a knowledge model that calculates patient satisfaction based on user feedback and measurable design features in a hospital environment;
•	Supervised research in post-occupancy studies in nursing homes;
•	Advisor for knowledge modelling ‘Longer independent living' Municipality of Rotterdam and safety medical technology for Ministry of Health;
•	Managed project costs in alignment with budgetary constraints and developed long/short term strategies to ensure achievement of objectives;
•	Co-developed the roadmap Healing Environments for both care and cure sector;

•	Co-developed and coordinated the faculty’s Health Research programme;
•	Managed and led a project for the re-use of nursing homes; Developed FlexTool and an operational knowledge model, which calculated the transformation potential of a building based on architectural characteristics.
•	Head Coordinator of 3TU Research Day ‘Innovation in Design and Management of Healthcare Facilities and Healthy Environments', in collaboration with TNO Dutch Centre for Health Assets;
•	Co-organiser of the national research day: ‘Thinking Differently, Designing Differently: Architecture in Health - Between Science and Practice’ , in collaboration with the Platform Architecture in Health, Netherlands Board for Healthcare Institutions and TU Delft;

EGM is one of the largest architectural firms in the Netherlands and provides high quality innovative building designs for the construction environment. 

• Responsible for improving product design, accelerating the initial stages of the design process and enhancing transparency of the decision making process;
•	Conducted research and increased revenue through securing profitable projects;
•	Led multiple projects in the field of specific user needs (such as homeless people, people with dementia) and embedding scientific research in design;
•	Developed a vision of design research and the possible role of science within the practice.
